               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430508-name-788" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-788" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-788" type="surname" value="LOCKYER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-788" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY LOCKYER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a policeman. On the night of the 21st of April I was in King-street, Westminster—I saw the prisoner running towards me with this box of cigars under his arm—I stopped him, and asked him where he had got them—he said he had picked them up in the road—he was fifteen or twenty yards from the prosecutor's shop—I took him to the shop, and asked the witness if she had missed these cigars—she went to the other side of the shop, and said she had—I took him to the station, and then he said a boy gave them to him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he not say about the boy the first time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430508-name-789" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-789" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-789" type="surname" value="OBBARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430508-name-789" type="given" value="MARGARET MATILDA"></interp>MARGARET MATILDA OBBARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my father, William Obbard, a tobacconist, in King-street, Westminster. The prisoner was brought to the shop by the policeman, with this box of cigars, which had been safe five minutes before—they are my father's.</p>
